Yeah, I think you know you've hit middle age when you've got the kids of your

33
00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:51.880
former trainees working in your lab.

34
00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:56.400
So that's always exciting. So I thought what we'd talk about

35
00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:00.140
today is molecular glues to induce cancer cell

36
00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:00.480
death.

37
00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:05.520
So these are my disclosures. Most relevant today is Shenandoah that's licensed some

38
00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:09.539
of the gain-of-function molecules. So I have sort of three parts.

39
00:02:09.940 --> 00:02:13.350
First, I want to convince you of the magic of chemically induced proximity,

40
00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:15.380
especially as it relates to gain-of-function.

41
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:19.580
And then I'm going to talk about using it to modulate the activity of two really

42
00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:23.060
critical transcription factors, BCL6 and p53.

43
00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:27.520
So as a field in oncology, we've been heavily

44
00:02:27.560 --> 00:02:31.200
focused on inhibition. So finding so-called

45
00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:34.000
cancer dependencies, and then inhibiting them.

46
00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:37.930
So mutant EGFR, mutant ALK, half of this

47
00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:40.220
meeting is about mutant RAS inhibitors.

48
00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:44.120
And of course, when you do that, you put the cells under extreme

49
00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:48.000
selective pressure to try to incur mutations or bypass

50
00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:52.180
signaling pathways. So we began to think, is there a fundamentally different

51
00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:56.060
way to target cancer through rewiring?

52
00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.100
Okay. So here the idea is we're not going to inhibit

53
00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:04.440
the oncogenic driver. We're going to redirect it to lead to a

54
00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:08.220
new function. Okay, so you've seen these kind of

55
00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:12.370
bivalent molecules most frequently in PROTACs for degradation,

56
00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:14.940
where you are degrading the target.

57
00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:18.810
But here what we're doing is we're trying to create a new signal that

58
00:03:18.820 --> 00:03:22.660
instead of leading to loss of function, actually leads to a gain of

59
00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:23.080
function.

60
00:03:24.280 --> 00:03:27.660
So the first place we started applying this was, could we

61
00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:31.340
create gain of function by creating a conduit

62
00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:34.940
between cancer drivers and the apoptotic pathway?

63
00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:35.950
So we know cells,

64
00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:40.180
when our bodies want to eliminate cells naturally, they don't

65
00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:43.800
inhibit the essential function of one protein, right?

66
00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:47.630
They induce the apoptotic cascade, and apoptosis,

67
00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:48.880
through

68
00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:53.460
programmed cell death, goes after many essential genes because you

69
00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:57.000
can't leave death to chance of just inhibiting one

70
00:03:57.020 --> 00:04:00.950
protein. So if you really want to eliminate cancer cells, you need to induce

71
00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:05.380
a more comprehensive program. So the idea here is can you create a

72
00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:09.000
sort of a short circuit between a cancer driver

73
00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:11.100
directly into the cell death pathway?

74
00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.960
So what are the steps for chemically induced proximity?

75
00:04:16.459 --> 00:04:19.810
So first, you have to have a target that you're going to go after.

76
00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:23.600
So in the case that we've been working on is transcription factors, but this could

77
00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:26.640
be any oncogenically associated protein.

78
00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:28.740
Then you have this recruitment step.

79
00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:32.860
And again, most people are familiar with PROTACs where the effector is an E3

80
00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:36.700
ligase. But now the effector can be something that will lead to a

81
00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:39.930
gain-of-function signal. And then finally, you get this

82
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.990
activation. And the examples I'll go through today are transcriptional

83
00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:48.130
rewiring. But you can imagine many other cellular fates, and you've people have

84
00:04:48.140 --> 00:04:51.140
probably heard about ones in this meeting involving

85
00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:54.660
multimerization, relocalization, induced

86
00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:57.240
phosphorylation, enhanced DNA damage.

87
00:04:57.680 --> 00:05:01.280
And the idea is substoichiometrically to lead to cell

88
00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:04.480
death through this new pathway.

89
00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:09.640
So one other really important point that I think gets confused is

90
00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:13.360
what's the fundamental difference between gain of function and

91
00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:17.520
loss of function? So all three modalities shown on the left,

92
00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:21.820
conventional inhibition, RIP-TAG, or degradation, are

93
00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.260
fundamentally loss-of-function approaches.

94
00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:28.540
So the idea is to fully eliminate a target in order to get

95
00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:30.820
the consequences of that elimination.

96
00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:34.860
And typically, the pharmacological effect requires complete

97
00:05:34.920 --> 00:05:38.440
elimination of that target, which either requires catalytic

98
00:05:38.460 --> 00:05:41.600
activity on the side of the ligase for degradation, or if it's an

99
00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:42.920
occupancy-based approach,

100
00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:47.380
like the classical rapamycin, cyclosporine type

101
00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:51.000
interaction where you fully sequester a protein with FKBP or cyclosporine,

102
00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:54.700
or with calcineurin, that's a full sequestration.

103
00:05:55.120 --> 00:05:58.969
So this is fundamentally different from a gain-of-pharmacology approach,

104
00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:02.940
right? So you're creating a neomorphic interaction in cells

105
00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:05.180
that leads to a fundamentally different outcome.

106
00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:08.940
And most outcomes we've looked at so far have been cell death, but you can

107
00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.600
imagine many other outcomes. And one of the

108
00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:16.110
fundamentally distinguishing qualities is this happens at a fractional

109
00:06:16.140 --> 00:06:19.780
occupancy. So you don't need a molecular glue that achieves

110
00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:21.500
stoichiometric binding of the target.

111
00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:24.840
You might only be hijacking 10% of the protein.

112
00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:26.740
And that means that you can get away

113
00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:30.617
withinteractions and small molecules that have much

114
00:06:30.617 --> 00:06:34.388
lower affinity because you're fundamentally achieving less receptor

115
00:06:34.468 --> 00:06:37.347
occupancy but still getting the cellular effect.

116
00:06:37.428 --> 00:06:39.608
So loss of function versus gain of function.

117
00:06:40.688 --> 00:06:42.128
So the first system that we've been

118
00:06:42.928 --> 00:06:46.768
characterizing has been BCL6. And here the idea

119
00:06:46.928 --> 00:06:50.908
was, BCL6 is known to be a death regulator and gets

120
00:06:50.948 --> 00:06:54.848
upregulated in lymphoma as a way of preventing cell

121
00:06:54.888 --> 00:06:58.768
death. So the idea we had together with Jerry Crabtree's lab was could

122
00:06:58.828 --> 00:07:02.768
you make a molecular glue that would convert BCL6 from being

123
00:07:02.808 --> 00:07:05.708
a transcriptional repressor to being a activator?

124
00:07:06.828 --> 00:07:10.608
So the idea is normally BCL6 epigenetically

125
00:07:10.628 --> 00:07:14.217
represses transcription by binding on

126
00:07:14.228 --> 00:07:17.658
chromatin, and it does so in complex with a whole series of

127
00:07:17.688 --> 00:07:21.488
corepressors. So chemists at Boehringer Ingelheim had built some very

128
00:07:21.568 --> 00:07:25.168
beautiful compounds that targeted the BTB domain.

129
00:07:25.188 --> 00:07:29.068
And so their idea at the time had been to de-repress by

130
00:07:29.077 --> 00:07:32.878
dissociating these corepressors, B-COR, N-COR, and

131
00:07:32.948 --> 00:07:36.588
SMART. So those compounds have some activity but don't lead to

132
00:07:36.648 --> 00:07:37.188
robust

133
00:07:38.308 --> 00:07:42.138
induction of apoptosis. So our idea was instead of just

134
00:07:42.148 --> 00:07:46.028
displacing those corepressors, now let's turbocharge the

135
00:07:46.068 --> 00:07:49.888
protein by recruiting in BRD4. So essentially we're

136
00:07:49.948 --> 00:07:53.488
creating now a synthetic transcription factor

137
00:07:53.908 --> 00:07:57.308
where you have a sort of Frankenstein interaction now between

138
00:07:57.348 --> 00:07:59.268
BRD4 and BCL6,

139
00:08:00.068 --> 00:08:03.908
and that then induces the expression of BCL6-dependent gene

140
00:08:03.968 --> 00:08:04.808
expression program.

141
00:08:06.668 --> 00:08:08.838
So what do these molecules look like in practice?

142
00:08:08.868 --> 00:08:11.668
So they kind of look like PROTAC-type molecules.

143
00:08:11.738 --> 00:08:15.648
So these are heterobifunctional molecules where on one side we

144
00:08:15.688 --> 00:08:19.398
have the BRD4 binder JQ1, and then this BTB domain

145
00:08:19.728 --> 00:08:23.168
binder. And whenever we do this chemistry, we make negative controls where we

146
00:08:23.228 --> 00:08:26.798
either disable binding on the left side or the right side by subtle mutations.

147
00:08:28.128 --> 00:08:32.108
And then we have a reporter gene assay, and this is fundamentally where you can see

148
00:08:32.168 --> 00:08:34.009
that it's a gain-of-function mechanism.

149
00:08:34.389 --> 00:08:37.768
So here, as we induce gluing between BRD4 and

150
00:08:37.808 --> 00:08:41.088
BCL6, we turn on a BCL6-dependent

151
00:08:41.168 --> 00:08:43.718
reporter with an EC50 of about five nanomolar.

152
00:08:44.208 --> 00:08:47.888
And classical of these molecular glues, it shows a hook-like

153
00:08:47.908 --> 00:08:51.868
behavior. So at a critical concentration, you stimulate ternary complex

154
00:08:51.888 --> 00:08:55.368
formation; too high or too low, and you don't get that effect.

155
00:08:56.648 --> 00:08:59.908
So what does this molecule do across chromatin?

156
00:09:00.308 --> 00:09:04.168
So if you do ChIP-seq for BRD4, you'll basically see

157
00:09:04.208 --> 00:09:07.748
that the molecule relocalizes BRD4 to

158
00:09:07.788 --> 00:09:10.838
BCL6 loci. And the consequence of that

159
00:09:10.868 --> 00:09:14.488
relocalization is to induce BCL6-dependent

160
00:09:14.768 --> 00:09:18.408
gene expression. So here are some of the key apoptotic proteins like

161
00:09:18.468 --> 00:09:19.928
NOXA, and you look at

162
00:09:20.788 --> 00:09:24.588
ChIP for RNA Pol II, you can see as a function of time, you

163
00:09:24.708 --> 00:09:28.348
rapidly induce RNA Pol II at the NOXA

164
00:09:28.368 --> 00:09:32.068
locus. And the reason this molecule is so wickedly potent

165
00:09:32.408 --> 00:09:35.968
is you're not simply inducing one gene, it's the entire

166
00:09:36.008 --> 00:09:39.128
BCL6 transcriptional program that gets activated.

167
00:09:40.108 --> 00:09:43.988
And it's actually a much more pronounced activation

168
00:09:44.308 --> 00:09:46.288
than you see if you just eliminate BCL6.

169
00:09:46.468 --> 00:09:50.048
So it's eliminating BCL6, then you no longer are

170
00:09:50.068 --> 00:09:53.648
repressing those genes, but now instead you're hyperactivating this

171
00:09:53.688 --> 00:09:57.548
expression. And so if you look at any measure of protein abundance

172
00:09:57.688 --> 00:10:01.457
in transcriptional changes, cell death, you get a much more pronounced

173
00:10:01.488 --> 00:10:04.128
effect with these kind of bivalent molecules.

174
00:10:04.788 --> 00:10:08.578
We've been able to show that these molecules work in vivo in collaboration with

175
00:10:08.608 --> 00:10:10.248
Michael Green's lab at MD Anderson.

176
00:10:10.548 --> 00:10:14.088
So these are lymphoma models that are heavily pretreated with

177
00:10:14.148 --> 00:10:18.008
previous chemotherapy. And what you can see is that you only see

178
00:10:18.068 --> 00:10:20.957
activity in models where BCL6 is high.

179
00:10:21.068 --> 00:10:24.448
So here we get nice control of tumor growth at quite modest

180
00:10:24.488 --> 00:10:28.308
doses. However, if you have a tumor model where it's BCL6 low

181
00:10:28.468 --> 00:10:32.088
or BCL6 negative, the cells grow right through this

182
00:10:32.108 --> 00:10:35.888
molecule. So again, this is a molecule that relies on

183
00:10:35.948 --> 00:10:39.918
hyperactivation of BCL6 to exert the activity and

184
00:10:39.968 --> 00:10:41.328
the induction of apoptosis.

185
00:10:42.728 --> 00:10:46.428
The other neat thing about these transcriptional inducers of proximity

186
00:10:46.888 --> 00:10:49.428
is it's not just one effector you can bring there.

187
00:10:49.788 --> 00:10:52.888
So we've actually now been able to extend this to two other effectors,

188
00:10:53.468 --> 00:10:55.348
CDK9, using this

189
00:10:56.368 --> 00:10:58.388
compound initially made by Bristol Myers Squibb,

190
00:10:59.408 --> 00:11:03.388
or a bromodomain binder of p300 to making a

191
00:11:03.768 --> 00:11:07.088
p300 BCL6 TIP. All of these can induce

192
00:11:07.128 --> 00:11:11.048
BCL6-dependent gene expression, but they do so in different ways,

193
00:11:11.128 --> 00:11:13.668
and you get different sets of genes that are activated.

194
00:11:14.128 --> 00:11:17.568
So with TIPs, unlike with the degrader, where fundamentally you're seeing loss of

195
00:11:17.588 --> 00:11:21.248
function, here you can get a different flavor of induction

196
00:11:21.508 --> 00:11:23.588
depending on the effector that you bring there.

197
00:11:23.958 --> 00:11:27.568
And these are now both published stories, so if you want to see the details, I

198
00:11:27.608 --> 00:11:28.648
refer you to those papers.

199
00:11:29.868 --> 00:11:31.368
So is this unique to

200
00:11:32.568 --> 00:11:36.108
BCL6? So another protein we started looking at was

201
00:11:36.348 --> 00:11:40.048
p53. So this has been well-recognized as

202
00:11:40.308 --> 00:11:43.648
the most universally dysregulated tumor suppressor.

203
00:11:44.048 --> 00:11:47.948
And there's been beautiful effort from a number of companies to make essentially

204
00:11:48.008 --> 00:11:51.988
corrector molecules. And so one of the mutants that's been attempted to be

205
00:11:52.028 --> 00:11:55.328
corrected is this Y220C, both with covalent and

206
00:11:55.348 --> 00:11:59.078
non-covalent molecules. Last year, there was a beautiful

207
00:11:59.088 --> 00:12:02.768
publication showing this rosettaphot can stabilize

208
00:12:02.808 --> 00:12:06.308
p53 and induce cell death. There was lots of preclinical work.

209
00:12:06.348 --> 00:12:10.138
And then beautiful clinical trial data published in "New

210
00:12:10.188 --> 00:12:14.078
England Journal of Medicine" showing sort of the first pharmacological

211
00:12:14.208 --> 00:12:16.988
evidence that you can reactivate a tumor suppressor.

212
00:12:17.028 --> 00:12:19.188
Obviously, you can't do that if the tumor suppressor is completely lost.

213
00:12:19.468 --> 00:12:21.508
But in this case, it's just a mutation.

214
00:12:22.088 --> 00:12:25.988
So we wanted to ask, can you further enhance this

215
00:12:26.268 --> 00:12:29.878
through a induced proximity interaction?So we did this

216
00:12:29.878 --> 00:12:33.708
again, recruiting BRD4. So we build a

217
00:12:33.748 --> 00:12:37.688
library of molecules, and then we screen them for their ability to induce

218
00:12:37.968 --> 00:12:41.668
ternary complex formation and induce gene expression,

219
00:12:42.608 --> 00:12:45.928
do a lot of chemistry similar to what you would do with PROTACs, understanding the

220
00:12:46.028 --> 00:12:48.408
optimal geometry of the linkers.

221
00:12:50.068 --> 00:12:53.728
And we found a compound here we call TRAP-1 for a

222
00:12:54.128 --> 00:12:58.028
activation molecule. So it's a p53, Y220C,

223
00:12:58.148 --> 00:13:01.328
BRD4 induced proximity molecule.

224
00:13:01.748 --> 00:13:05.648
You get nice induction of protein-protein interaction, and then

225
00:13:05.688 --> 00:13:09.228
that's associated with turning on p53 dependent

226
00:13:09.648 --> 00:13:13.588
expression. So in this case, the molecules are not as potent as we

227
00:13:13.628 --> 00:13:17.468
saw for BCL6, but conceivably with more medicinal

228
00:13:17.488 --> 00:13:18.988
chemistry, they can be further optimized.

229
00:13:19.428 --> 00:13:23.128
But you can really see robust activation of p53 dependent

230
00:13:23.348 --> 00:13:26.778
genes. So for example, p21, MDM2, very

231
00:13:26.908 --> 00:13:30.408
strongly activated by these molecules leading to enhanced

232
00:13:30.968 --> 00:13:34.888
cellular effects. So again, this is not a pure

233
00:13:34.948 --> 00:13:38.488
p53 stabilization. You're now creating a chimera

234
00:13:38.528 --> 00:13:42.508
between this p53 stabilizer and BRD4.

235
00:13:43.948 --> 00:13:47.908
But many times you actually don't have a binder to the factor

236
00:13:47.948 --> 00:13:51.388
that you want to look at. And so one factor we wanted to look at is

237
00:13:51.508 --> 00:13:55.348
EWS-FLI. This is a driver oncogene in Ewing

238
00:13:55.428 --> 00:13:58.828
sarcoma that we've collaborated with Kim Stegmaier's lab,

239
00:13:59.448 --> 00:14:02.618
and we basically made a fusion protein with

240
00:14:02.668 --> 00:14:06.448
FKBP, and then we made, similar to the dTag

241
00:14:06.508 --> 00:14:09.708
system for degradation, this sort of a dTag system for

242
00:14:10.148 --> 00:14:14.108
transcriptional activation. We could then build a bivalent between the

243
00:14:14.148 --> 00:14:17.888
