and this work was led by Megan, Olivia, and CJ in my lab.

489
00:28:19.370 --> 00:28:22.970
It was a fantastic collaboration with Xiao Wen in Ning Jiang's lab,

490
00:28:23.390 --> 00:28:24.410
as well as many others.

491
00:28:25.750 --> 00:28:29.710
And so when we first embarked on this study, we faced many difficulties in

492
00:28:29.770 --> 00:28:32.970
trying to find the binding site, let alone the target of

493
00:28:33.030 --> 00:28:36.640
UM171, which we assumed was CoREST, the protein that

494
00:28:36.730 --> 00:28:38.410
was directly being degraded.

495
00:28:39.230 --> 00:28:43.180
But this actually turned out to be much more complicated, and for today's talk, I'm

496
00:28:43.190 --> 00:28:46.900
going to jump to the punchline. But it turns out that the actual

497
00:28:47.010 --> 00:28:50.710
target of UM171 was not on anyone's radar

498
00:28:50.770 --> 00:28:53.410
because it's not actually degraded in this mechanism.

499
00:28:53.950 --> 00:28:57.930
But it turned out to be histone deacetylase 1 and 2, what I'll call HDAC for

500
00:28:57.970 --> 00:29:00.590
short, a key partner protein to CoREST.

501
00:29:01.390 --> 00:29:05.370
And with all of those key players identified, we could solve a Cryo-EM

502
00:29:05.410 --> 00:29:07.570
structure with all the components put together.

503
00:29:08.290 --> 00:29:12.069
And what this revealed was that indeed, UM171 acts as a

504
00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:16.010
molecular glue, recruiting this dimeric E3 ligase to

505
00:29:16.050 --> 00:29:19.670
a single copy of HDAC in an asymmetric manner.

506
00:29:21.210 --> 00:29:25.139
And so I think that there are a lot of really interesting insights and

507
00:29:25.170 --> 00:29:29.130
novelties associated with this structure and mechanism since UM171

508
00:29:29.170 --> 00:29:33.010
is the first molecular glue discovered to hijack a dimeric

509
00:29:33.090 --> 00:29:34.050
E3 ligase.

510
00:29:34.930 --> 00:29:38.770
But for today's talk, I'm going to focus on the small molecule

511
00:29:38.910 --> 00:29:42.390
binding site. And so if we zoom in, we see that UM171

512
00:29:42.470 --> 00:29:46.400
partially occupies the active site of HDAC, close to

513
00:29:46.470 --> 00:29:50.150
its catalytic zinc atom. And on the E3 ligase side, it induces a

514
00:29:50.190 --> 00:29:53.990
groove between blade two and three of this kelch propeller

515
00:29:54.070 --> 00:29:54.550
domain.

516
00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:59.450
Now, really what we can tell from this structure is that this small

517
00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:03.050
molecule protein composite surface is really quite extensive.

518
00:30:03.570 --> 00:30:06.950
And based on the complexities of this, at least to me, it's

519
00:30:07.010 --> 00:30:10.560
inconceivable how a molecule like this could have been prospectively designed.

520
00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:15.130
Now, I'd like to point out one key feature in this structure, what is called the

521
00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:18.090
2B2C loop of the ligase, highlighted here in blue.

522
00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:22.730
This loop makes contact not only with UM171, but also

523
00:30:22.890 --> 00:30:26.820
HDAC itself. And so it's a critical interaction hotspot in this ternary

524
00:30:26.870 --> 00:30:30.770
complex interface. Now, I'm pointing out the position of this loop

525
00:30:30.850 --> 00:30:34.620
because it turns out to be a cancer mutation hotspot in

526
00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:36.710
certain subtypes of medulloblastoma.

527
00:30:37.710 --> 00:30:41.230
Now, these cancer mutations are actually quite fascinating.

528
00:30:41.250 --> 00:30:45.030
While they can involve point mutations, what actually is most common in

529
00:30:45.070 --> 00:30:48.990
patients are the in-frame insertion of one or two amino acids into

530
00:30:49.030 --> 00:30:49.510
that loop.

531
00:30:50.710 --> 00:30:53.890
And so when we first started this project, we had no idea what these cancer

532
00:30:53.930 --> 00:30:57.300
mutations were doing.But what we did know was that the

533
00:30:57.390 --> 00:31:01.210
wild-type ligase could somehow degrade coREST by

534
00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:04.970
involving UM171. And so based off of that

535
00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:07.890
connection, we tested the impact of these cancer

536
00:31:07.950 --> 00:31:10.790
mutations on coREST protein levels.

537
00:31:11.590 --> 00:31:15.370
To do this, we engineered a cell line where GFP was knocked into the

538
00:31:15.390 --> 00:31:19.130
endogenous coREST gene, and so we could measure protein levels

539
00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:20.070
using fluorescence.

540
00:31:21.070 --> 00:31:24.650
And what we found using this system, totally unexpected to us at the time,

541
00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:28.570
was that these cancer mutations in the ligase, they could actually

542
00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:32.470
induce coREST degradation even in the absence of

543
00:31:32.530 --> 00:31:36.360
UM171. And so these cancer mutations actually turned

544
00:31:36.430 --> 00:31:40.379
out to be gain-of-function. And while loss-of-function mutations in

545
00:31:40.390 --> 00:31:44.090
the E3 ligases are really well established, this is one of the first

546
00:31:44.110 --> 00:31:48.040
examples of a gain-of-function mutation that can cause the recruitment and

547
00:31:48.130 --> 00:31:51.770
degradation of a new substrate. And I'll call this mechanism

548
00:31:51.870 --> 00:31:53.210
neodegradation for short.

549
00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:57.030
But how is this neodegradation actually taking place?

550
00:31:57.960 --> 00:32:01.710
And so to investigate this mechanism, we first profiled the

551
00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:05.650
landscape of mutations at that 2B2C loop that could

552
00:32:05.710 --> 00:32:09.350
cause this coREST neodegradation using a method called deep

553
00:32:09.410 --> 00:32:12.470
mutational scanning, what I'll call DMS for short.

554
00:32:13.410 --> 00:32:17.090
To do this, we first designed an overexpression library of these

555
00:32:17.130 --> 00:32:20.750
KBDBD4 mutants concentrated along the seven amino

556
00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:24.810
acids of this 2B2C loop. This library could cover all

557
00:32:24.870 --> 00:32:28.690
single amino acid substitutions, all double substitutions of

558
00:32:28.710 --> 00:32:32.510
adjacent residues, as well as all plus one and plus two amino

559
00:32:32.590 --> 00:32:36.330
acid insertions inspired by those cancer variants.

560
00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:37.960
We could then introduce this

561
00:32:39.370 --> 00:32:43.090
KBDBD4 library in a pooled fashion

562
00:32:43.150 --> 00:32:46.930
into that coREST GFP cell line I showed you before, and we could

563
00:32:47.030 --> 00:32:50.930
specifically sort for cells that go GFP dark to identify these

564
00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:53.630
mutations that cause coREST degradation.

565
00:32:54.810 --> 00:32:58.790
Now, at a really high level, it turned out that it's shockingly easy

566
00:32:58.800 --> 00:33:01.730
to cause coREST neodegradation in this system.

567
00:33:02.470 --> 00:33:06.450
And so each dot on this plot shows a different mutation that we could test, over

568
00:33:06.750 --> 00:33:10.690
5,000 of them. And I think what's most striking is that these plus two

569
00:33:10.710 --> 00:33:14.470
insertions shown here in the darkest red, they really work the best by a

570
00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:18.470
long shot. And that matches the fact that they're also the most prevalent

571
00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:20.370
found in these medulloblastomas.

572
00:33:21.710 --> 00:33:25.290
And so to really understand why these plus two insertions are so

573
00:33:25.350 --> 00:33:28.930
effective, especially for the cancer variants, we next solve the

574
00:33:28.970 --> 00:33:32.230
cryo-EM structures of two distinct KBDBD4

575
00:33:32.270 --> 00:33:35.550
mutants bound to the HDAC coREST complex.

576
00:33:35.570 --> 00:33:37.830
We chose what I'll call the PR mutant for short.

577
00:33:38.120 --> 00:33:39.950
This is the most common clinical variant.

578
00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:44.150
It involves the insertion of a proline and arginine residue into that

579
00:33:44.290 --> 00:33:47.790
2B2C loop. We also chose what I'll call TTYML,

580
00:33:48.230 --> 00:33:51.970
a more complex mutation that still results in an overall plus

581
00:33:52.010 --> 00:33:52.290
two.

582
00:33:53.350 --> 00:33:56.550
Now, both of these mutated ligases exhibit a similar

583
00:33:56.710 --> 00:34:00.050
engagement of HDAC to what I showed you before.

584
00:34:00.810 --> 00:34:04.750
And in fact, in one of these E3 ligase protomers, we see that the cancer

585
00:34:04.770 --> 00:34:08.650
insertion, highlighted here in yellow, makes direct contact with the

586
00:34:08.850 --> 00:34:11.810
HDAC active site. So a little bit of deja vu.

587
00:34:13.011 --> 00:34:16.330
If we zoom in here, what we see is that in comparison to the wild-type

588
00:34:16.390 --> 00:34:20.230
ligase overlayed in gray, that the mutants extend

589
00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:24.180
that 2B2C loop into the HDAC active site by creating

590
00:34:24.230 --> 00:34:27.980
a bump on the protein surface. And critically, it's that

591
00:34:28.031 --> 00:34:31.770
central arginine of the PR mutant, which is inserted deep into the

592
00:34:31.950 --> 00:34:35.571
HDAC catalytic pocket, whereas it is the tyrosine in the

593
00:34:35.611 --> 00:34:39.531
corresponding position of TTYML that fulfills that same purpose.

594
00:34:40.200 --> 00:34:43.970
And from our deep mutational scanning, we know that it's that central inserted

595
00:34:44.071 --> 00:34:47.730
residue that's one of the key hotspots driving this

596
00:34:47.810 --> 00:34:51.650
neointeraction. In fact, from our DMS, we actually know all

597
00:34:51.710 --> 00:34:55.390
possible combinations of two amino acids that can essentially fit

598
00:34:55.450 --> 00:34:57.469
into and interact with that pocket.

599
00:34:58.930 --> 00:35:01.790
Now, I think what's really curious here is that

600
00:35:01.930 --> 00:35:05.590
UM171 also contacts this 2B2C loop,

601
00:35:06.010 --> 00:35:09.870
as well as the HDAC active site. And so what's its relationship to these

602
00:35:09.910 --> 00:35:10.950
cancer insertions?

603
00:35:12.509 --> 00:35:15.890
If we actually superimpose these two structures on top of one another,

604
00:35:16.410 --> 00:35:20.170
what we see is that the cancer insertion and the small molecule, they

605
00:35:20.250 --> 00:35:24.000
actually exactly mimic one another, not only functionally,

606
00:35:24.270 --> 00:35:27.710
but also structurally, through, again, what I'll call chemical genetic

607
00:35:27.750 --> 00:35:31.610
convergence. And so I think this is really striking, and so I'll walk

608
00:35:31.650 --> 00:35:33.110
you through this step by step.

609
00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:37.890
And so we can imagine that UM171, it has these three different arms in

610
00:35:37.930 --> 00:35:41.090
its structure. The first arm, this diamino

611
00:35:41.150 --> 00:35:44.770
cyclohexane, it makes polar contacts with these two acidic

612
00:35:44.830 --> 00:35:48.410
residues in HDAC, aspartate 99, glutamate 98.

613
00:35:49.160 --> 00:35:52.930
And that's just like threonine 311 in the TTYML mutant.

614
00:35:53.810 --> 00:35:57.740
The second arm, the tetrazole, is inserted deep into the HDAC active site,

615
00:35:58.130 --> 00:36:01.610
in this case resembling that central tyrosine and arginine of the cancer

616
00:36:01.630 --> 00:36:02.300
insertion.

617
00:36:03.170 --> 00:36:06.750
And lastly, this third arm, the benzyl group, in this case resembles

618
00:36:06.790 --> 00:36:10.579
methionine 313. And so these three arms of

619
00:36:10.650 --> 00:36:14.310
UM171, these different functional groups, they actually mirror the

620
00:36:14.350 --> 00:36:16.730
different side chains of the amino acid

621
00:36:16.770 --> 00:36:20.760
insertions. So in essence, the wild-type ligase and

622
00:36:20.810 --> 00:36:24.570
HDAC, they have this imperfect interface, which allows for

623
00:36:24.610 --> 00:36:24.910
weak

624
00:36:25.950 --> 00:36:29.170
basal interaction, but it's not good enough for degradation to

625
00:36:29.230 --> 00:36:33.110
happen. These cancer insertions provide a bump on the ligase

626
00:36:33.150 --> 00:36:36.830
surface that can fill in the adjacent hole made up by the HDAC

627
00:36:36.930 --> 00:36:40.700
active site. And it's those bump hole interactions that

628
00:36:40.730 --> 00:36:43.990
glue together this otherwise suboptimal interface.

629
00:36:44.650 --> 00:36:47.470
And that's exactly analogous to the mechanism of action of

630
00:36:47.550 --> 00:36:51.290
UM171, showing that the mechanism of a small

631
00:36:51.370 --> 00:36:55.210
molecule, molecular glue, and what we'll call a cancer

632
00:36:55.250 --> 00:36:58.790
mutation genetic glue, in this case, can actually work through the same

633
00:36:58.810 --> 00:37:02.630
principles.And so altogether, we could

634
00:37:02.690 --> 00:37:06.570
reveal these converging mechanisms of this gain-of-function cancer

635
00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:10.550
mutation in an E3 ligase and the mechanism of a

636
00:37:10.590 --> 00:37:14.390
small molecule molecular gludegrader, UM171, showing that they

637
00:37:14.450 --> 00:37:17.449
work as molecular facsimiles of one another.

638
00:37:18.410 --> 00:37:22.020
But taking a step back, I think this highlights a really interesting

639
00:37:22.170 --> 00:37:25.950
case where genetics and a mutation could

640
00:37:26.030 --> 00:37:29.360
actually reveal a glueable hotspot, a genetic

641
00:37:29.410 --> 00:37:32.970
glue on a E3 ligase surface, whose

642
00:37:32.990 --> 00:37:36.810
effects could be exactly recapitulated by the engagements of a small

643
00:37:36.850 --> 00:37:39.590
molecule through this chemical genetic convergence.

644
00:37:40.230 --> 00:37:42.910
And I think this raises a really interesting thought experiment.

645
00:37:43.670 --> 00:37:47.430
If we knew everything about that cancer mutation, the deep

646
00:37:47.490 --> 00:37:51.230
mutational scanning data, the cryo-EM structures, but we

647
00:37:51.290 --> 00:37:55.190
knew nothing about UM171, could we have actually

648
00:37:55.370 --> 00:37:59.270
harnessed that data to perspectively design a molecular glue?

649
00:38:00.590 --> 00:38:04.430
And so along those lines, I think what's very fascinating is that both of these

650
00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:08.390
modalities, the small molecule and the mutation, they're both

651
00:38:08.430 --> 00:38:12.130
neomorphic. They confer hyperactivation on an E3 ligase.

652
00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:16.590
And beyond the context of medulloblastoma or hematopoietic stem

653
00:38:16.710 --> 00:38:20.010
cells, hyperactivation of KBDBD4 is actually

654
00:38:20.050 --> 00:38:23.950
cytotoxic to most cells. And so in unpublished data, we

655
00:38:23.970 --> 00:38:27.470
have shown that UM171 in the broad prism screen

656
00:38:27.910 --> 00:38:31.410
is broadly anti-proliferative in many human cancer cell lines.

657
00:38:32.310 --> 00:38:35.990
Likewise, we have seen that overexpression of this mutant

658
00:38:36.130 --> 00:38:39.790
E3 ligase can also block the growth of many human

659
00:38:39.890 --> 00:38:43.690
cancer cell lines through what we'll call an activation lethality.

660
00:38:44.410 --> 00:38:47.810
This led us to wonder, could we actually use this activation

661
00:38:47.890 --> 00:38:51.370
lethality phenotype in a cell death readout to

662
00:38:51.450 --> 00:38:55.400
identify these gain-of-function mutations on these ligases,

663
00:38:55.470 --> 00:38:58.570
these genetic glues, that might actually go after new

664
00:38:58.630 --> 00:38:59.540
neosubstrates?

665
00:39:00.790 --> 00:39:04.450
And so with that in mind, to explore this, we could conduct that deep

666
00:39:04.510 --> 00:39:07.330
mutational scanning of the 2B2C loop,

667
00:39:08.130 --> 00:39:11.610
just like I showed you before. But instead of only measuring co-REST

668
00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:15.150
degradation, we could also read out cell proliferation

669
00:39:15.530 --> 00:39:18.850
and drop out due to this activation lethality.

670
00:39:19.570 --> 00:39:21.150
And so the data is shown on your right.

671
00:39:21.610 --> 00:39:25.590
The x-axis shows us just co-REST degradation, the exact data

672
00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:29.390
that I showed you before. But now the y-axis is showing

673
00:39:29.470 --> 00:39:33.150
us the cell proliferation associated with each of these mutants,

674
00:39:33.510 --> 00:39:36.209
and also dropout due to this activation lethality.

675
00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:40.410
And so mutants in the lower right-hand corner, these are very effective at

676
00:39:40.450 --> 00:39:43.799
degrading co-REST and also essentially killing these cells,

677
00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:46.860
actually revealing that the two activities are correlated.

678
00:39:47.310 --> 00:39:50.950
And just as we expected, we see that the cancer mutants, which are very

679
00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:53.840
potent, reside in this lower right-hand corner.

680
00:39:54.850 --> 00:39:58.610
And so I think what this highlights is how we can use this activation lethality

681
00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:02.310
phenotype in a cell death readout to identify

682
00:40:02.320 --> 00:40:05.930
these genetic glues of E3 ligases, even

683
00:40:05.970 --> 00:40:09.410
without knowing the substrate that's being degraded.

684
00:40:11.030 --> 00:40:14.730
And so based on these results, we've been having a lot of fun using deep

685
00:40:14.770 --> 00:40:18.630
mutational scanning to find these glueable

686
00:40:18.710 --> 00:40:22.550
hotspots, these genetic glues of E3s, and also the

687
00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:24.370
neosubstrates associated with them.

688
00:40:25.070 --> 00:40:28.870
And so first, we can conduct this high-throughput mutational scanning

689
00:40:28.930 --> 00:40:32.590
across the surface of these E3 ligase substrate receptors.

690
00:40:33.590 --> 00:40:37.420
And we can then take essentially this library of bumped variants and

691
00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:40.090
select them in different cell-based phenotypic readouts,

692
00:40:40.990 --> 00:40:44.430
with the idea that we can identify these, again, rare

693
00:40:44.530 --> 00:40:48.510
gain-of-function genetic glues that might actually go after

694
00:40:48.650 --> 00:40:49.750
new neosubstrates.

695
00:40:50.630 --> 00:40:54.570
I showed you how we could use readouts like degradation of specific targets

696
00:40:54.670 --> 00:40:57.540
or cell proliferation, but there are many ways that we can imagine this.

697
00:40:58.350 --> 00:41:01.910
And through proteomics, we can actually identify these neosubstrates involved.

698
00:41:02.750 --> 00:41:06.340
Now, I think the outstanding question, the million-dollar question, is

699
00:41:06.410 --> 00:41:10.370
whether you can actually replace this genetic glue, this bump

700
00:41:10.430 --> 00:41:13.590
on the protein surface, with a small molecule.

701
00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:18.310
And as chemical biologists, these are questions that we're actively exploring,

702
00:41:18.430 --> 00:41:20.390
and we hope to report on this in due time.

703
00:41:22.170 --> 00:41:24.930
So that brings me to this presentation's most important slide.

704
00:41:25.030 --> 00:41:28.950
I, of course, have to thank everyone who did all of the work involved, our really

705
00:41:29.010 --> 00:41:32.520
fantastic collaborators, Xiao Wen in Ning's lab, as well as many others.

706
00:41:32.920 --> 00:41:36.150
I have to thank our funding sources and acknowledge my disclosures.

707
00:41:36.170 --> 00:41:39.020
Thank you for attention. I'll stop here. I'm happy to take any questions.

708
00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:53.030
Okay, questions. I will

709
00:41:53.870 --> 00:41:55.970
start if I can. Great. Okay, so

710
00:41:56.930 --> 00:41:58.940
fascinating concept that,

711
00:41:59.830 --> 00:42:00.970
if I understood it correctly,

712
00:42:01.850 --> 00:42:05.790
you might posit that insertions of one or two amino acids might be more

713
00:42:05.830 --> 00:42:09.600
effective at creating surface neomorphic outcomes that

714
00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:13.050
promote degradation than just missense mutation. Is that a fair statement or no?

715
00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:15.510
Yeah, that's definitely a fair statement.

716
00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:19.030
For us, we found that these insertions were most effective.

717
00:42:19.070 --> 00:42:22.770
And actually, insertions have been more rarely studied.

718
00:42:22.950 --> 00:42:23.130
Yeah.

719
00:42:23.470 --> 00:42:27.190
But of the reports coming out from, for example, Ben Leonard's lab and

720
00:42:27.270 --> 00:42:30.580
others, it seems like they're more privileged at promoting these

721
00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:32.270
gain-of-function interactions.

722
00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:32.300
Very interesting.

723
00:42:32.310 --> 00:42:35.610
And so I think prioritizing them makes a lot of sense.

724
00:42:36.290 --> 00:42:39.730
And is it right so far, your approach you're taking is somewhat random at the amino

725
00:42:39.790 --> 00:42:41.670
acids you insert, or do you have a logic?

726
00:42:42.430 --> 00:42:46.360
Yeah, I think right now we're just taking an approach of trying

727
00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:50.350
everything, even though it's a bit bigger in terms of mutation space that we need

728
00:42:50.390 --> 00:42:54.159
to explore. But one could definitely think about prioritizing

729
00:42:54.210 --> 00:42:58.110
hydrophobic amino acids or even unnatural amino acids

730
00:42:58.130 --> 00:42:59.870
in the future.

731
00:42:59.930 --> 00:43:00.450
Great. Thanks.

732
00:43:01.898 --> 00:43:05.718
A really nice talk. I'm just interested in actually using your

733
00:43:05.858 --> 00:43:09.798
UM17 to actually displace in the mutant setting.

734
00:43:10.178 --> 00:43:13.198
So can you actually now restore

735
00:43:13.238 --> 00:43:16.878
the death effect in the mutant

736
00:43:16.998 --> 00:43:18.718
case of the ligase?

737
00:43:19.218 --> 00:43:20.858
Yeah, no, that's an excellent question.

738
00:43:20.978 --> 00:43:23.958
So what we found was, so UM17-1,

739
00:43:25.698 --> 00:43:29.658
interestingly, can actually cooperate with the cancer mutations to some extent.

740
00:43:30.098 --> 00:43:30.278
But

741
00:43:31.798 --> 00:43:35.718
what we noticed, of course, was that it's really the HDAC active site that's a

742
00:43:35.778 --> 00:43:39.738
critical interaction hotspot. And so what we found was that HDAC

743
00:43:39.878 --> 00:43:43.258
active site inhibitors could actually block that interaction.

744
00:43:43.278 --> 00:43:44.098
Mm-hmm.

745
00:43:44.518 --> 00:43:48.378
I think actually what would be more ideal is if one had ligands for the

746
00:43:48.418 --> 00:43:51.938
ligase side, since then you would not have an HDAC inhibitor.

747
00:43:51.978 --> 00:43:55.278
But as a proof of concept, that worked really well to restore

748
00:43:56.458 --> 00:43:58.578
levels of that co-res protein complex.

749
00:43:59.458 --> 00:43:59.778
Thanks.

750
00:44:03.258 --> 00:44:03.838
Great talk.

751
00:44:05.258 --> 00:44:09.138
Thought it was pretty interesting that the mutation that actually shows

752
00:44:09.218 --> 00:44:12.078
up, at least one of them, is positively charged, and a lot of-

753
00:44:12.398 --> 00:44:12.518
Yeah

754
00:44:12.538 --> 00:44:16.018
... a lot of active site HDAC binders are negatively charged.

755
00:44:16.578 --> 00:44:19.238
I guess that's probably a surprise to you guys as well.

756
00:44:19.278 --> 00:44:20.518
Do you understand what's going on there?

757
00:44:21.438 --> 00:44:21.698
Yeah.

758
00:44:22.538 --> 00:44:26.438
So that insertion of an arginine, or even the arginine seemed to be

759
00:44:26.538 --> 00:44:30.458
very privileged. Even a point mutation that put an

760
00:44:30.518 --> 00:44:33.138
arginine into that pocket was very effective.

761
00:44:34.478 --> 00:44:38.178
We thought that what might be going on, we did not have the resolution to see it,

762
00:44:38.298 --> 00:44:41.798
was that since it's a zinc deacetylase,

763
00:44:42.318 --> 00:44:45.678
that there should be an active site water that's critical in the mechanism.

764
00:44:46.218 --> 00:44:46.638
And so,

765
00:44:47.498 --> 00:44:50.798
our hypothesis was that it was forming some sort of interaction there.

766
00:44:50.978 --> 00:44:54.318
But until we actually resolve that, this is just speculation.

767
00:44:54.958 --> 00:44:55.558
Okay, thanks a lot.

768
00:44:57.778 --> 00:44:59.978
Okay, Brian, thanks a bunch. That was really excellent.

769
00:45:04.298 --> 00:45:04.438
As

770
00:45:05.758 --> 00:45:09.548
Brian mentioned, our next speaker, Steven Corsello from Stanford, is one of

771
00:45:09.598 --> 00:45:13.378
the NextGen stars, and so congratulations,

772
00:45:13.438 --> 00:45:15.658
Steven, on that recognition from the AACR.

773
00:45:16.558 --> 00:45:19.858
And he's going to tell us some really interesting work about the relationship

774
00:45:19.878 --> 00:45:23.458
between E3 ligase and nuclear pore protein degradation. Steven.

775
00:45:24.978 --> 00:45:26.188
Great. Well, thank you so much, Dr.

776
00:45:26.358 --> 00:45:30.158
Krivat, and thank you to the AACR for this recognition.

777
00:45:34.998 --> 00:45:38.918
My lab uses systematic cellular-based assays in order to identify

778
00:45:38.928 --> 00:45:42.478
drug mechanisms and cancer vulnerabilities.

779
00:45:42.498 --> 00:45:46.228
And starting when I was at the Broad Institute, we launched an effort to first

780
00:45:46.278 --> 00:45:50.178
collect the active ingredient from as many drugs tested in humans

781
00:45:50.218 --> 00:45:53.878
as possible, and then profile that library across its

782
00:45:53.918 --> 00:45:55.418
different phenotypic readouts.

783
00:45:56.418 --> 00:45:59.588
One of those approaches that has proven to be the most fruitful for finding

784
00:45:59.638 --> 00:46:03.468
anti-cancer mechanisms has been systematic cell viability profiling.

785
00:46:04.178 --> 00:46:07.918
And we accomplish this using the prism pooled screening strategy,

786
00:46:08.558 --> 00:46:12.498
where individual cancer cell lines are first labeled with unique DNA

787
00:46:12.578 --> 00:46:16.018
barcode sequences. And this allows us to pool the models

788
00:46:16.038 --> 00:46:19.938
together and much more efficiently test compounds for signs

789
00:46:19.958 --> 00:46:23.698
of anti-cancer activity. We use the barcodes as a surrogate for cell

790
00:46:23.718 --> 00:46:27.338
viability and then compare the barcode abundance in treated versus

791
00:46:27.378 --> 00:46:31.178
control wells. And we initially reported a

792
00:46:31.218 --> 00:46:34.658
data set of more than 4,000 drugs across more than

793
00:46:34.918 --> 00:46:38.878
500 cancer cell lines in order to define the initial drug

794
00:46:38.958 --> 00:46:41.918
response landscape of human cancer cell lines.

795
00:46:42.538 --> 00:46:46.478
And you'll see that at this high-level 2D representation of the drug

796
00:46:46.558 --> 00:46:50.138
activity profiles, drugs do tend to cluster

797
00:46:50.538 --> 00:46:52.978
by their known targets and mechanisms.

798
00:46:54.438 --> 00:46:58.258
We were most interested, though, in hunting for compounds with new

799
00:46:58.318 --> 00:47:01.818
patterns of anti-cancer activity, and we found several dozen

800
00:47:01.898 --> 00:47:04.438
compounds acting in unexpected ways.

801
00:47:05.038 --> 00:47:08.148
And a lot of our interest has been taking those compounds back to the lab and

802
00:47:08.238 --> 00:47:12.138
figuring out how they work. And in general, they've tended to work in

803
00:47:12.218 --> 00:47:14.838
modes of action beyond enzyme inhibition.

804
00:47:15.418 --> 00:47:18.998
So it seems like these phenotypic approaches can help enrich for interesting

805
00:47:19.078 --> 00:47:22.918
mechanisms, including some of the gain-of-function pharmacology that we've learned

806
00:47:22.978 --> 00:47:24.178
about during this session.

807
00:47:25.538 --> 00:47:29.388
In order to get a start in identifying the targets of these compounds,

808
00:47:29.458 --> 00:47:31.138
we take a predictive modeling approach.

809
00:47:32.018 --> 00:47:35.348
Since these cell lines have been extensively characterized by the Cancer Cell Line

810
00:47:35.398 --> 00:47:39.178
Encyclopedia project, we can systematically compare the

811
00:47:39.198 --> 00:47:42.998
molecular features, such as which genes are high or low, which copy number events

812
00:47:43.038 --> 00:47:46.238
have occurred, or what mutations are present in the cells.

813
00:47:46.258 --> 00:47:50.128
And we compare those against all of the drug activity profiles through

814
00:47:50.158 --> 00:47:51.747
random forest predictive modeling.

815
00:47:52.338 --> 00:47:56.328
And this yields a set of predictive models along with features and

816
00:47:56.358 --> 00:47:59.918
feature weights. And in some cases, this has given us strong initial

817
00:47:59.978 --> 00:48:03.038
insight into how these compounds might be acting.

818
00:48:04.298 --> 00:48:08.138
Most recently, we've used these types of screening approaches in order to

819
00:48:08.218 --> 00:48:12.038
look for new therapeutic opportunities in difficult-to-treat cancers.

820
00:48:12.798 --> 00:48:16.658
And one of the most difficult remains pancreatic adenocarcinoma, and this

821
00:48:16.718 --> 00:48:20.538
is a disease I treat in the clinic. There are over 50,000 deaths per

822
00:48:20.718 --> 00:48:24.298
year from pancreatic cancer in the United States alone.

823
00:48:24.338 --> 00:48:28.198
And our mainstay of therapy for patients with advanced disease remains

824
00:48:28.218 --> 00:48:30.258
cytotoxic chemotherapy regimens.

825
00:48:30.778 --> 00:48:34.478
And even with our most aggressive combination of three chemotherapy drugs, a

826
00:48:34.518 --> 00:48:38.498
regimen called FOLFIRINOX, the median overall survival remains just

827
00:48:38.558 --> 00:48:42.438
around one year. We're quite excited about reports at this meeting

828
00:48:42.498 --> 00:48:44.878
and likely some targeted therapies coming soon.

829
00:48:45.298 --> 00:48:48.638
I think it remains clear that we really will need multiple targets in order to

830
00:48:48.698 --> 00:48:50.718
achieve more cures in this disease.

831
00:48:52.298 --> 00:48:55.798
So a postdoc in my group, Linji Wan, began to look for new

832
00:48:55.898 --> 00:48:59.798
therapeutic opportunities, and we came across a drug that had been

833
00:48:59.838 --> 00:49:03.378
in phase one testing, known as PRLX 93936.

834
00:49:03.918 --> 00:49:07.786
And across all of the cell lines testedIt was more likely

835
00:49:07.826 --> 00:49:11.726
to inhibit pancreas and head and neck cancer cell models versus the

836
00:49:11.806 --> 00:49:14.886
other cancer types tested in this experiment.

837
00:49:14.906 --> 00:49:17.706
In addition, there was a strong predictive biomarker.

838
00:49:18.386 --> 00:49:22.316
We found that expression of an E3 ligase called TRIM21

839
00:49:22.806 --> 00:49:26.706
strongly predicted sensitivity, and you'll see if you look at all of the

840
00:49:26.746 --> 00:49:30.286
cell lines, the cell lines that had high expression by RNA seq of

841
00:49:30.326 --> 00:49:34.276
TRIM21 were more likely to be sensitive to this

842
00:49:34.306 --> 00:49:34.786
compound.

843
00:49:35.906 --> 00:49:38.076
The compound had a really interesting development history.

844
00:49:38.586 --> 00:49:42.386
It was first synthesized about 20 years ago by a company named Prolexis

845
00:49:42.406 --> 00:49:45.886
Pharmaceuticals, and their initial goal was to take this tool

846
00:49:45.986 --> 00:49:49.806
compound on the left, a compound called erastin, which is

847
00:49:49.946 --> 00:49:53.816
famous for being the prototypic inducer of a form of programmed

848
00:49:53.866 --> 00:49:57.846
cell death called ferroptosis. They tried to turn erastin into a clinical

849
00:49:58.006 --> 00:50:01.896
drug, and through medicinal chemistry optimization, they succeeded in

850
00:50:01.966 --> 00:50:04.486
making it more potent and more drug-like.

851
00:50:04.946 --> 00:50:08.806
But there was a big catch. In the course of the optimization, they actually

852
00:50:08.866 --> 00:50:12.856
changed the mechanism of action, so it was no longer acting through

853
00:50:12.866 --> 00:50:16.246
ferroptosis, but instead was killing cancer cells

854
00:50:16.446 --> 00:50:19.846
through a traditional form of programmed cell death, apoptosis.

855
00:50:20.746 --> 00:50:24.456
Despite not knowing the target, this was advanced into two phase I trials

856
00:50:24.826 --> 00:50:27.166
where they generated some initial safety data.

857
00:50:27.286 --> 00:50:30.986
But ultimately, the program was abandoned, and the compound was put on the

858
00:50:31.006 --> 00:50:31.346
shelf.

859
00:50:32.406 --> 00:50:35.886
So we took this into the lab and started just by confirming that the pooled

860
00:50:35.966 --> 00:50:39.656
screening result could be reproduced by testing individual cell lines.

861
00:50:40.166 --> 00:50:44.006
We selected these cell lines based on their TRIM21 status, and indeed, all

862
00:50:44.046 --> 00:50:47.946
of the TRIM21 expressing cell lines were sensitive, and cell

863
00:50:47.986 --> 00:50:51.806
lines with low TRIM21 expression were completely resistant,

864
00:50:52.366 --> 00:50:55.426
thus recapitulating the prism screening result.

865
00:50:56.486 --> 00:51:00.386
We were then interested to identify functional mediators of response

866
00:51:00.526 --> 00:51:04.506
to this drug, PRLX, and we did this using a functional genomic strategy where

867
00:51:04.546 --> 00:51:08.406
we took a pancreatic cancer cell line, derivatized it to express a

868
00:51:08.466 --> 00:51:12.326
Cas9 protein, and then transduced these cells with genome-scale guide RNA

869
00:51:12.446 --> 00:51:16.426
libraries. We then cultured that mixture of genetic perturbation in

870
00:51:16.465 --> 00:51:20.206
the presence of the compound for several weeks, and then looked for gene level

871
00:51:20.306 --> 00:51:24.186
perturbations that could rescue from the compound or sensitize.

872
00:51:25.186 --> 00:51:28.626
In our initial CRISPR knockout screen, we found that the top hit

873
00:51:28.786 --> 00:51:32.606
across the entire genome that recognized from this drug was

874
00:51:32.666 --> 00:51:36.606
TRIM21 as well. So it was not only a predictive biomarker, it's actually

875
00:51:36.646 --> 00:51:37.966
the top functional mediator.

876
00:51:38.766 --> 00:51:42.286
In addition, we did a screen in the opposite direction using CRISPR activation,

877
00:51:42.356 --> 00:51:44.646
where we overexpressed every gene in the genome.

878
00:51:45.146 --> 00:51:48.806
And there, one of the top sensitization hits was TRIM21.

879
00:51:48.886 --> 00:51:51.206
So this phenotype actually works in both directions.

880
00:51:51.726 --> 00:51:55.516
Several other hits in the screen included multiple mediators of

881
00:51:55.586 --> 00:51:57.846
NF Kappa B and interferon signaling.

882
00:52:00.246 --> 00:52:01.846
We then tested individual cell lines.

883
00:52:02.086 --> 00:52:04.506
So what happens if we perturb TRIM expression?

884
00:52:04.546 --> 00:52:07.896
And here we found if we take a TRIM21 expressing line and knock out

885
00:52:07.986 --> 00:52:11.636
TRIM21, there's a complete rescue from response to the

886
00:52:11.726 --> 00:52:15.586
compound, whereas with erastin, that original parent compound, there's absolutely

887
00:52:15.626 --> 00:52:19.266
no shift. And then we also could take TRIM21 low cell

888
00:52:19.326 --> 00:52:22.926
lines that were resistant to the compound, overexpress

889
00:52:22.986 --> 00:52:26.666
TRIM21, and confer sensitivity. So this turned out to be a really nice

890
00:52:26.786 --> 00:52:29.206
binary phenotype for further study.

891
00:52:30.286 --> 00:52:33.926
So TRIM21 is a really unique ring family E3

892
00:52:33.966 --> 00:52:37.516
ubiquitin ligase that serves as a bridge between innate and

893
00:52:37.566 --> 00:52:41.346
adaptive immunity. Its native function has actually been shown

894
00:52:41.506 --> 00:52:45.166
to be to bind intracellular antibodies, and this is

895
00:52:45.186 --> 00:52:49.046
mediated through an interaction between the TRIM21 PRI SPry domain

896
00:52:49.566 --> 00:52:53.186
and the FC region of IgG antibodies.

897
00:52:53.906 --> 00:52:57.866
Upon binding an antibody often bound to a pathogen

898
00:52:57.946 --> 00:53:01.196
inside of a cell, this leads to ubiquitylation and

899
00:53:01.306 --> 00:53:04.766
proteasome-mediated degradation of that large cargo,

900
00:53:05.306 --> 00:53:08.686
and TRIM appears to be particularly evolved to degrade large multimeric

901
00:53:08.746 --> 00:53:12.506
substrates. This also activates interferon signaling

902
00:53:12.516 --> 00:53:16.006
within cells. So by some measures, this might actually be an immune

903
00:53:16.126 --> 00:53:20.046
sensor as well. So we then hypothesized

904
00:53:20.086 --> 00:53:24.046
that TRIM21 might actually be the direct molecular target of

905
00:53:24.105 --> 00:53:27.605
this drug, PRLX. And to begin to figure this out, we also used a

906
00:53:27.646 --> 00:53:31.406
mutational scanning approach using CRISPR base editing, where we tiled the

907
00:53:31.446 --> 00:53:35.406
entire coding sequence of TRIM21 with guide RNAs, and we found

908
00:53:35.446 --> 00:53:39.406
that the rescuing mutations tended to cluster at three different

909
00:53:39.466 --> 00:53:42.926
sites, one of which was at the natural substrate

910
00:53:43.006 --> 00:53:46.936
recognition domain of TRIM21, which coincided in the crystal

911
00:53:47.026 --> 00:53:50.926
structure with the location of a shallow binding

912
00:53:50.966 --> 00:53:54.626
pocket. So we hypothesized that the PRI SPry domain was the

913
00:53:54.666 --> 00:53:57.146
direct target of this molecule.

914
00:53:58.346 --> 00:54:02.326
We then expressed recombinant TRIM21 PRI SPry and

915
00:54:02.366 --> 00:54:06.126
succeeded in obtaining a ligand-bound crystal structure of a PRLX

916
00:54:06.206 --> 00:54:09.766
analog. This allowed us to confirm that the base editing result was

917
00:54:09.846 --> 00:54:13.526
correct, and it also showed us the direct amino acid

918
00:54:13.586 --> 00:54:17.506
interactions between TRIM21 and

919
00:54:17.846 --> 00:54:21.646
this compound. And then using both our isogenic cell line

920
00:54:21.746 --> 00:54:25.146
system as well as the structural information later on,

921
00:54:25.886 --> 00:54:29.626
we were able to team up with our neighbors at Stanford, in Nathaniel Gray's

922
00:54:29.666 --> 00:54:33.446
lab, to establish the structure activity relationship of

923
00:54:33.506 --> 00:54:36.196
this compound series against TRIM21.

924
00:54:36.826 --> 00:54:40.666
And through the synthesis of many chemical analogs, we

925
00:54:40.706 --> 00:54:44.586
succeeded in both improving the potency as well as dramatically

926
00:54:44.626 --> 00:54:45.886
improving the

927
00:54:46.746 --> 00:54:50.726
properties of these molecules. The original drug was administered intravenously

928
00:54:50.746 --> 00:54:53.216
in the clinic on what might've been a suboptimal schedule.

929
00:54:53.596 --> 00:54:56.826
And now we have the opportunity to actually give these agents orally.

930
00:54:57.446 --> 00:55:01.416
And then this compound shown on the right, JWZ8103,

931
00:55:01.726 --> 00:55:05.626
also helped enable our biochemical assays in order to figure out the

932
00:55:05.646 --> 00:55:09.426
mechanism of action. It turned out having a more potent compound early on was

933
00:55:09.466 --> 00:55:13.266
quite helpful in that regard.So now we

934
00:55:13.326 --> 00:55:17.026
had an example of an E3 ligase whose

935
00:55:17.466 --> 00:55:20.026
expression is essential for response to this compound.

936
00:55:20.786 --> 00:55:24.686
We next asked whether this might be another example of targeted

937
00:55:24.706 --> 00:55:28.456
protein degradation. And to begin to study this, we performed

938
00:55:28.506 --> 00:55:30.366
three different proteomic experiments.

939
00:55:30.926 --> 00:55:33.616
We looked at changes in protein abundance.

940
00:55:34.226 --> 00:55:37.936
We also looked for changes in ubiquitin marks on proteins through

941
00:55:37.966 --> 00:55:41.736
diglycine remnant profiling. And finally, we developed a proximity

942
00:55:41.826 --> 00:55:45.606
labeling approach using TurboID to look if this molecule was actually

943
00:55:45.626 --> 00:55:49.346
inducing changes in the TRIM21 interactome.

944
00:55:50.046 --> 00:55:53.896
And it turned out that all three of these proteomic experiments led us to the

945
00:55:53.986 --> 00:55:57.806
same targets, which were multiple components of the nuclear

946
00:55:57.906 --> 00:56:01.676
pore complex, this large multimeric substrate that

947
00:56:01.726 --> 00:56:05.666
serves as the gateway between the cytoplasm and nucleus.

948
00:56:06.126 --> 00:56:09.946
And we saw that many, almost all of the nucleoporins were

949
00:56:09.986 --> 00:56:13.856
labeled in the TurboID experiment, were ubiquitinated, and

950
00:56:13.886 --> 00:56:16.686
were subsequently degraded in a

951
00:56:16.746 --> 00:56:20.626
TRIM21-dependent manner. We saw no proteins degraded

952
00:56:20.646 --> 00:56:24.026
in cells with TRIM21 knockout.

953
00:56:25.156 --> 00:56:27.516
We were also able to assess this on a single-cell level.

954
00:56:27.806 --> 00:56:31.486
This is an immunofluorescence image of pancreatic cancer cells.

955
00:56:31.506 --> 00:56:35.306
And here, if we treat with the molecular glue for eight hours, we see

956
00:56:35.406 --> 00:56:38.896
loss of nuclear pore expression along the nuclear membrane.

957
00:56:39.446 --> 00:56:42.666
And importantly, we did not see any loss of expression with

958
00:56:42.706 --> 00:56:44.426
TRIM21 knockout.

959
00:56:45.506 --> 00:56:49.446
So then the next question was: How is TRIM21 actually recruited

960
00:56:49.766 --> 00:56:53.646
to the nuclear pore complex? And to begin to understand this, we actually

961
00:56:53.666 --> 00:56:57.116
went back to our original CRISPR screen and realized we'd overlooked something

962
00:56:57.146 --> 00:57:00.996
initially when we looked at the results summarized at the gene level.

963
00:57:01.006 --> 00:57:04.266
It turned out that one of the four guides against the nucleoporin

964
00:57:04.346 --> 00:57:08.306
Nup98 that's present in the Brunello library actually

965
00:57:08.546 --> 00:57:12.246
rescued from the compound, whereas the other guides were actually depleted because

966
00:57:12.256 --> 00:57:16.196
this is an essential gene. And we found that the single active guide

967
00:57:16.346 --> 00:57:20.206
targeted a special spot on the gene that encodes

968
00:57:20.226 --> 00:57:22.246
something called the autoproteolytic domain.

969
00:57:22.735 --> 00:57:26.626
It turns out that Nup98 and Nup96 are encoded as one polypeptide

970
00:57:26.646 --> 00:57:30.446
precursor. It gets cleaved at this site to generate the

971
00:57:30.466 --> 00:57:31.706
mature protein forms.

972
00:57:32.686 --> 00:57:36.486
Then we transduced cells with that guide alone and found that that was

973
00:57:36.546 --> 00:57:40.226
actually enough to also completely rescue from

974
00:57:40.486 --> 00:57:44.046
these TRIM21-directed compounds, suggesting that the

975
00:57:44.186 --> 00:57:47.876
Nup98 APD was the key

976
00:57:48.026 --> 00:57:50.376
site of interaction with TRIM21.

977
00:57:51.526 --> 00:57:55.446
We then assessed for direct molecular glue interaction using several approaches,

978
00:57:55.566 --> 00:57:58.706
and were able to show that TRIM21 directly binds

979
00:57:59.086 --> 00:58:02.686
Nup98 in cells with a NanoBit reporter assay.

980
00:58:02.926 --> 00:58:06.806
Here we found that compound rank order nicely agreed with

981
00:58:06.846 --> 00:58:10.146
their cellular cytotoxicity. And we were also able to

982
00:58:10.166 --> 00:58:13.846
recapitulate this interaction in vitro through TR-FRET

983
00:58:13.866 --> 00:58:17.366
experiments where we expressed recombinant Nup98 APD.

984
00:58:18.106 --> 00:58:21.186
And we had similar results using SPR as well.

985
00:58:21.866 --> 00:58:24.986
So these compounds are indeed molecular glues that directly recruit

986
00:58:25.326 --> 00:58:27.706
TRIM21 to Nup98.

987
00:58:28.716 --> 00:58:31.726
They also appear to have potent anticancer properties.

988
00:58:31.786 --> 00:58:35.166
And as had been originally reported 20 years ago, they do induce

989
00:58:35.246 --> 00:58:37.786
apoptosis through the intrinsic pathway.

990
00:58:38.506 --> 00:58:42.436
We see a robust activation of a Caspase reporter within 12 hours of

991
00:58:42.526 --> 00:58:45.646
treatment. This also occurs in a TRIM21-dependent manner.

992
00:58:46.766 --> 00:58:50.586
Next, given how important nuclear transport is in gene expression

993
00:58:50.646 --> 00:58:54.286
to export mature mRNAs from the nucleus to

994
00:58:54.346 --> 00:58:55.086
cytoplasm,

995
00:58:55.906 --> 00:58:59.566
we hypothesized that maybe these molecules in part act

996
00:58:59.586 --> 00:59:03.556
by decreasing the expression of proteins that cancers need for

997
00:59:03.586 --> 00:59:07.086
survival. And we'd indeed already seen some hints of this in our

998
00:59:07.126 --> 00:59:10.806
proteomic data. But we found that proteins that are

999
00:59:10.866 --> 00:59:14.626
famous for having short cellular half-lives, like MCL1 and

1000
00:59:14.706 --> 00:59:18.566
MYC, are dramatically reduced upon degradation of the nuclear

1001
00:59:18.666 --> 00:59:22.306
pore complex in cancer cells. And at the mRNA level,

1002
00:59:22.626 --> 00:59:24.666
we're able to see this, for example, for MCL1.

1003
00:59:25.146 --> 00:59:28.816
Within four hours of compound treatment, cytoplasmic MCL1

1004
00:59:28.906 --> 00:59:32.726
goes down, or as it actually goes up within the nucleus, likely

1005
00:59:32.765 --> 00:59:36.066
because those mRNAs can no longer be exported

1006
00:59:36.746 --> 00:59:38.086
out of the nucleus themselves.

1007
00:59:39.166 --> 00:59:43.086
Then specific to pancreatic cancer, a quick summary of the

1008
00:59:43.126 --> 00:59:46.966
mechanism. So these molecules, we believe, directly bind

1009
00:59:47.146 --> 00:59:50.626
TRIM21, which is then recruited to the nuclear pore

1010
00:59:50.686 --> 00:59:53.406
complex through an interaction with Nup98.

1011
00:59:53.416 --> 00:59:57.086
And then this leads to labeling of the NPC with ubiquitin

1012
00:59:57.326 --> 01:00:01.236
marks. This is then degraded in a proteasome-dependent manner,

1013
01:00:01.246 --> 01:00:05.146
which disrupts nucleocytoplasmic transport and then results

1014
01:00:05.186 --> 01:00:07.486
in apoptotic cancer cell death.

1015
01:00:08.546 --> 01:00:12.276
And then specific to pancreatic cancer, we went on to test patient-derived models

1016
01:00:12.326 --> 01:00:15.766
and PDOs in vitro. And there, TRIM21

1017
01:00:15.786 --> 01:00:17.476
expression predicted their sensitivity.

1018
01:00:18.126 --> 01:00:21.406
And we also saw encouraging evidence in cell line xenograft studies.

1019
01:00:21.446 --> 01:00:24.686
And these are two different KRAS mutant cancer cell lines.

1020
01:00:25.246 --> 01:00:28.806
And in both models, we saw robust efficacy,

1021
01:00:28.926 --> 01:00:32.226
especially for an optimized derivative, this JWZ compound

1022
01:00:32.266 --> 01:00:36.096
again, where just after several days of daily dosing, we saw

1023
01:00:36.126 --> 01:00:39.246
immediate tumor regressions in these mice,

1024
01:00:39.686 --> 01:00:43.486
suggesting that this could be a valuable approach for future

1025
01:00:43.496 --> 01:00:43.996
development.

1026
01:00:45.516 --> 01:00:49.466
There remain, though, really two unanswered questions, and the first is: Well,

1027
01:00:49.506 --> 01:00:53.326
what is the therapeutic index really for targeting nuclear transport

1028
01:00:53.336 --> 01:00:56.996
in cancer versus normal cells? And this remains an area of active

1029
01:00:57.026 --> 01:01:00.656
investigation, though we certainly learned a lot from literature reports,

1030
01:01:00.726 --> 01:01:04.546
including some evidence that genetic depletion of the nuclear

1031
01:01:04.666 --> 01:01:08.656
pore complex more affects cancer cells versus normal

1032
01:01:08.686 --> 01:01:12.416
cells. And inspired by this and other work, we're now

1033
01:01:12.486 --> 01:01:16.479
doingComparing the sensitivity of cancer cells versus immortalized

1034
01:01:16.550 --> 01:01:20.500
normal cancer cells, where we exposed them to TRIM21 glues for

1035
01:01:20.550 --> 01:01:24.110
defined periods. Here is just one example where if we treat for

1036
01:01:24.270 --> 01:01:27.450
24 hours, we see about a 23-fold shift in the

1037
01:01:27.490 --> 01:01:30.920
sensitivity between PANCS-1 cells and

1038
01:01:31.090 --> 01:01:33.010
hTERT-RPE-1 cells.

1039
01:01:34.250 --> 01:01:38.090
A second unaddressed question remains, well, multiple

1040
01:01:38.250 --> 01:01:41.530
groups have really performed pioneering work over the past several years

1041
01:01:41.570 --> 01:01:45.430
showing that there's a range of different compounds that

1042
01:01:45.470 --> 01:01:48.250
can induce a TRIM21 glue interaction.

1043
01:01:48.770 --> 01:01:52.650
And it's actually somewhat surprising how different these compounds are, and they

1044
01:01:52.670 --> 01:01:56.550
can all induce gluing between TRIM21 and NUP98.

1045
01:01:56.630 --> 01:02:00.350
So what really explains why this exists

1046
01:02:00.450 --> 01:02:01.480
in nature,

1047
01:02:02.390 --> 01:02:05.510
and to date, we'd only really had structural insight to the

1048
01:02:05.570 --> 01:02:08.450
TRIM21 side of the equation, which was quite limiting.

1049
01:02:09.750 --> 01:02:13.720
So working together with Stephen Hinshaw at Stanford, we recently succeeded

1050
01:02:13.770 --> 01:02:16.950
in solving the ternary complex between

1051
01:02:16.970 --> 01:02:20.750
TRIM21 and the NUP98 APE, and there's a number of really interesting

1052
01:02:20.850 --> 01:02:24.470
features here. One is that the NUP98 surface itself,

1053
01:02:24.660 --> 01:02:28.630
perhaps like we've seen with other molecular glues, is relatively indistinct

1054
01:02:28.690 --> 01:02:32.130
and flat in nature, and not something that you might have predicted through

1055
01:02:32.170 --> 01:02:34.850
computational methods as having been the binding site.

1056
01:02:35.550 --> 01:02:39.450
And while we do see direct interactions between the compound

1057
01:02:39.690 --> 01:02:43.270
and NUP98, it actually seems like most of the

1058
01:02:43.310 --> 01:02:46.880
interaction is really mediated through protein-protein contacts,

1059
01:02:47.290 --> 01:02:49.240
and there's an extensive network of these contacts.

1060
01:02:49.350 --> 01:02:50.990
One example is shown here on the right.

1061
01:02:51.790 --> 01:02:55.430
And we think that this will have important implications for both further

1062
01:02:55.470 --> 01:02:59.170
optimization of these compounds, but also in efforts to

1063
01:02:59.210 --> 01:03:03.040
reprogram TRIM21 against other substrates in order to take advantage of

1064
01:03:03.070 --> 01:03:06.450
its preference for large multimeric substrates.

1065
01:03:07.670 --> 01:03:11.270
So in conclusion, we found that TRIM21 molecular glues have potent

1066
01:03:11.350 --> 01:03:13.610
efficacy against pancreatic cancer models.

1067
01:03:14.170 --> 01:03:17.690
We've been able to establish their mechanism of action using multiple orthogonal

1068
01:03:17.750 --> 01:03:21.290
approaches. And our next steps are really focused on determining the

1069
01:03:21.330 --> 01:03:25.050
preclinical therapeutic index, further in vivo evaluation,

1070
01:03:25.250 --> 01:03:27.750
and advancing these molecules in development.

1071
01:03:28.650 --> 01:03:32.130
So I'd like to thank everyone in my group and all of our outstanding collaborators,

1072
01:03:32.690 --> 01:03:34.690
both at Stanford and at the Broad Institute.

1073
01:03:34.719 --> 01:03:36.750
And thank you all for your attention.

1074
01:03:36.770 --> 01:03:39.450
I'd be delighted to answer any questions.

1075
01:03:46.770 --> 01:03:49.690
That was a great talk. Shiva Malik from Novartis.

1076
01:03:50.750 --> 01:03:54.690
I noticed IRF2 was a hit in your screens,

1077
01:03:54.810 --> 01:03:58.770
and I was just thinking an alternative or potentially

1078
01:03:58.970 --> 01:04:02.450
a mechanism that might also be happening is you're actually blocking

1079
01:04:02.510 --> 01:04:06.250
degradation of another substrate. So did you look for that?

1080
01:04:07.310 --> 01:04:11.010
IRF2 being one, but potentially maybe there's other substrates that are blocked and

1081
01:04:11.070 --> 01:04:14.189
that's actually what's causing the cell death versus what you're seeing.

1082
01:04:14.830 --> 01:04:17.210
Yeah. Thank you for the question. It's a fascinating idea.

1083
01:04:17.250 --> 01:04:21.200
I think the IRF1 and 2 link here turns out to be quite interesting, and I

1084
01:04:21.210 --> 01:04:24.030
think they turn out to actually be both upstream and downstream of

1085
01:04:24.070 --> 01:04:27.270
TRIM21, which has made studying them a little harder.

1086
01:04:27.450 --> 01:04:31.320
We do know that when we knock out IRF2, that also completely rescues from this

1087
01:04:31.350 --> 01:04:35.130
mechanism. However, one reason is TRIM21 expression actually

1088
01:04:35.170 --> 01:04:35.910
goes down.

1089
01:04:36.040 --> 01:04:36.210
Mm.

1090
01:04:36.330 --> 01:04:39.030
And IRF1 and 2 drive expression of TRIM21.

1091
01:04:39.370 --> 01:04:43.250
But that being said, when we treat with the glues, the first gene to go up is IRF1,

1092
01:04:43.810 --> 01:04:46.879
which then itself gets degraded in a proteasome-mediated manner.

1093
01:04:47.430 --> 01:04:51.260
So there seems to be a really closely evolved feedback loop within

1094
01:04:51.310 --> 01:04:54.250
cells involving these IRF1 and 2 signaling proteins.

1095
01:04:54.290 --> 01:04:57.610
But I think it actually could be quite interesting to think about proteomics-based

1096
01:04:57.650 --> 01:05:01.170
approaches there as well in the setting of IRF1 or 2 loss.

1097
01:05:03.170 --> 01:05:06.750
So following up actually on the expression levels of TRIM21.

1098
01:05:06.930 --> 01:05:07.150
So,

1099
01:05:08.070 --> 01:05:11.730
the expression level of TRIM21 varies quite widely across

1100
01:05:11.790 --> 01:05:15.490
cancers. So you can imagine that you won't be able to use this

1101
01:05:15.730 --> 01:05:19.390
molecular glue in all settings. So can you actually learn any

1102
01:05:19.450 --> 01:05:23.230
insights from that molecular glue that you can use to target the nuclear

1103
01:05:23.330 --> 01:05:26.690
pore using more ubiquitously expressed ligases?

1104
01:05:27.650 --> 01:05:31.530
Yes, and absolutely. I think that part of the selectivity here could in part

1105
01:05:31.569 --> 01:05:33.770
come from the TRIM21 expression pattern.

1106
01:05:34.160 --> 01:05:37.550
It does tend to be highly expressed, especially when

1107
01:05:37.590 --> 01:05:41.400
comparing cancer versus matched normal tissue, higher in

1108
01:05:41.450 --> 01:05:43.690
pancreas and head and neck cancers in general.

1109
01:05:43.730 --> 01:05:46.190
So I do think that cell line observation will hold up.

1110
01:05:46.530 --> 01:05:49.970
We are interested in looking at primary patient tumors and kind

1111
01:05:50.010 --> 01:05:53.730
of defining that strategy now in order to really better understand its expression

1112
01:05:53.790 --> 01:05:57.250
pattern. But at least some of the selectivity will hopefully come from the

1113
01:05:57.290 --> 01:05:58.490
expression pattern.

1114
01:05:58.510 --> 01:05:59.610
And great talk, by the way.

1115
01:05:59.710 --> 01:06:00.850
Thank you.

1116
01:06:01.750 --> 01:06:05.570
Hi there. There are companies looking at TRIM TACS

1117
01:06:06.450 --> 01:06:10.110
that they're using to degrade CNS aggregates for

1118
01:06:10.170 --> 01:06:13.970
neurodegenerative diseases. Have you looked at your compounds in

1119
01:06:14.230 --> 01:06:17.430
neurodegenerative aggregates and clearing of those?

1120
01:06:18.490 --> 01:06:22.270
Yeah, so that's an area of active work right now, and I think a number of those

1121
01:06:22.310 --> 01:06:25.710
efforts are quite exciting and I think are taking advantage of what's been shown to

1122
01:06:25.750 --> 01:06:29.040
be a rather unique avidity-driven amplification

1123
01:06:29.850 --> 01:06:33.690
mechanism around TRIM21. The fact that it could degrade the entire

1124
01:06:33.810 --> 01:06:37.680
NPC is quite special. So I think that there's a lot of opportunity

1125
01:06:37.770 --> 01:06:41.610
there. I think some of the rules around TRIM21 PROTAC

1126
01:06:41.650 --> 01:06:44.330
design still remain to be established.

1127
01:06:44.830 --> 01:06:47.720
And right now, there's a lot of interest in figuring out what the best TRIM

1128
01:06:47.770 --> 01:06:51.550
recruiter is going to be. One interesting thing I think

1129
01:06:51.590 --> 01:06:55.490
explained by the crystal structure now is that the monovalent binding of

1130
01:06:55.530 --> 01:06:58.330
many of these ligands for TRIM21 is actually relatively weak.

1131
01:06:58.800 --> 01:06:58.800
Okay.

1132
01:06:58.890 --> 01:07:01.370
So the protein-protein interaction does a lot of that lifting.

1133
01:07:01.950 --> 01:07:05.670
So I think it remains to be seen if a glue-based approach, taking advantage of

1134
01:07:05.730 --> 01:07:09.660
complementary protein surfaces will ultimately be the most potent efficacious,

1135
01:07:10.110 --> 01:07:13.600
or if bivalent PROTACs will really work out.

1136
01:07:13.710 --> 01:07:16.930
But I think there is some initial proof of concept work that at least shows it's

1137
01:07:16.950 --> 01:07:20.350
feasible. And I hope it'll be something that can be translated.

1138
01:07:20.410 --> 01:07:20.690
Thank you.

1139
01:07:21.670 --> 01:07:24.560
Last question.Hi, nice work.

1140
01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:28.300
TRIM21 is very good, as you said, at getting multimeric proteins.

