01:08:36.820 --> 01:08:40.800
thinking about developing induced proximity modalities

1163
01:08:41.181 --> 01:08:44.860
and share a few vignettes of how powerful it can be to take these

1164
01:08:44.900 --> 01:08:46.340
systems-level approaches.

1165
01:08:47.181 --> 01:08:48.880
So I'll start with my disclosures.

1166
01:08:50.500 --> 01:08:54.340
And the question that we're really interested in as a lab

1167
01:08:54.400 --> 01:08:57.900
that's a chemical biology lab, but at its core is really

1168
01:08:57.920 --> 01:09:01.280
interested in doing the medicinal chemistry of chemical biology to

1169
01:09:01.340 --> 01:09:05.320
create chemical tools that can enable

1170
01:09:05.400 --> 01:09:09.130
us to validate new targets, and in particular, validate pharmacological

1171
01:09:09.260 --> 01:09:12.700
modulation of new targets in a way that allows

1172
01:09:12.760 --> 01:09:16.240
us to pursue them therapeutically.

1173
01:09:16.260 --> 01:09:20.200
But also look at some of these proteins that come out of screens

1174
01:09:20.240 --> 01:09:24.141
or that come out of genetic studies that are perhaps not very well annotated.

1175
01:09:24.450 --> 01:09:27.740
And those of you who have done that will know that it's a surprising number of

1176
01:09:27.780 --> 01:09:28.360
proteins.

1177
01:09:29.280 --> 01:09:32.900
And so one of the big questions, if you're thinking about these

1178
01:09:32.960 --> 01:09:36.780
problems and you're in the field of induced proximity, and one that you might

1179
01:09:36.880 --> 01:09:40.721
be asking yourself, having seen all of the amazing work in both this session

1180
01:09:41.120 --> 01:09:44.840
as well as the chemistry to the clinic sessions this weekend, are

1181
01:09:44.980 --> 01:09:48.061
how do you match your target and your

1182
01:09:48.080 --> 01:09:51.530
indication to the right induced proximity modality?

1183
01:09:51.580 --> 01:09:55.350
If you've determined that a simple, well, not simple, but if you've determined that

1184
01:09:55.400 --> 01:09:59.240
a traditional inhibitor is not what you need, how do you

1185
01:09:59.280 --> 01:10:02.630
know if you can indeed create a molecular glue?

1186
01:10:03.210 --> 01:10:07.200
What type of molecular glue, gain-of-function or loss-of-function pharmacology

1187
01:10:07.400 --> 01:10:11.220
would you want? And then how do you know that any hits or leads you may

1188
01:10:11.260 --> 01:10:14.870
get are advanceable, and how can you advance them quickly to really

1189
01:10:14.920 --> 01:10:17.360
prove that this mechanism is the right one for you?

1190
01:10:17.780 --> 01:10:21.520
Because even though we are all really excited about the space, the

1191
01:10:21.620 --> 01:10:22.740
space is very new.

1192
01:10:24.420 --> 01:10:27.880
And so something that my lab has

1193
01:10:27.920 --> 01:10:31.820
invested a lot of time in is creating profiling

